{
  "text": "Immunity Suppressive Roles of MyD88 Signaling in B Cells mRNA was strongly upregulated in CD138 + cells (but not in CD138 À cells) both at days 1 and 3 p.i. (Figure 5C ). We then used the B-Green reporter strain to characterize the dynamic of this B cell response during the course of Salmonella infection. Notably, the frequency of GFP-expressing cells among CD138 + B cells was maximum at day 1 p.i., when it was proportional to the number of bacteria administered and decreased thereafter ( Figure 5D ). Approximately 50% of splenic CD19 + CD138 + cells expressed eGFP at 24 hr p.i. with 10 7 colony forming unit (CFU) Salmonella ( Figure 5D ). Remarkably, this early response was markedly diminished in B-Myd88 À/À mice compared to + B cells in spleen via a MyD88-dependent pathway. To assess the role of IL-10 expression by B cells in vivo, we generated B-Il10 À/À mice by reconstituting irradiated JHT mice with a mixture of BM cells from JHT mice (80%) and Il10-deficient mice (20%). Control chimera was obtained by reconstituting irradiated JHT mice with BM cells from C57BL/6 mice (80%) and Il10 À/À mice (20%). Remarkably, B-Il10 À/À mice showed improved survival after infection with virulent Salmonella, indicating that IL-10 production by B cells inhibited protection (Figure 6A) . The similar improvement of survival seen in infected B-Il10 À/À and B-Myd88 À/À mice, together with the impaired development of IL-10-expressing B cells in B-Myd88 À/À mice, suggested to us that IL-10 could be an important mediator of the suppression resulting from intrinsic MyD88 signaling in B cells during Salmonella infection. To examine this notion further, we characterized the innate and adaptive immune responses of B-Il10 À/À mice infected with Salmonella. Notably, lack of IL-10 in B cells was associated with heightened infiltration of immune cells in infected livers, so that B-Il10 À/À mice had $2-fold more inflammatory foci than B-WT mice at day 6 p.i. (Figures 6B and  6C) , as previously seen for B-Myd88 À/À mice ( Figure 2C ). Similarly, B-Il10 À/À mice displayed enhanced neutrophil and NK cell responses after infection with either attenuated or virulent Salmonella (Figures 6D and 6E) . We also found, as previously described during EAE [CITATION_1] , that IL-10 production by B cells strongly suppressed the specific CD4 + T cell response to Salmonella: B-Il10 À/À mice had more IFN-gproducing CD4",
